      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Hillston ¶ NSW. ¶  ¶ 4th September 1882 ¶ Baron ¶  ¶ In obedience to your commands I went yesterday in search of the acacia ¶ See A. Grant to M, 12 August 1882(in this edition as 82-08-12a). ¶  ¶ and ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">82.09.04a</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Andrew<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Grant</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M113, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter found with a specimen of<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Acacia<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     </seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">h</seg>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">omalophylla</seg>
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(MEL 30261);<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>the AVH entry (accessed 30 March 2024) has a note<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">'Supplied scientific name "Acacia omalophylla</seg>"'.</p>
               </note>Hillston<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>NSW.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>4th September 1882</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In obedience to your commands I went yesterday in search of the acacia<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See A. Grant to M, 12 August 1882<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>(in this edition as 82-08-12a).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>and as I anticipated it is now gone out of flower for some time and the seed pods are as you will observe formed. I however continued the search for over nine Miles and got one little flower which I placed the end of the sprig it is on in a different – a contrary direction from the others. It is a pretty plant and some plants much prettier than others I never saw it grow on the North side of Lachlan nor so far as I can recollect south of the Murrumbidgie.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Lachlan and Murrumbidgee Rivers, NSW.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Towards the Mountains in the Creeks and Gullies of which the acacia decurrens occurs and the habitat of this plant there is a wide belt in which neither of the plants grow. The decurrens often has a stem of several feet this one seldom has as many inches – generally separating at the surface into many branches The gum in which it is very prolific I think also tastes different. I never observed sheep eat the spray of this plant but I have known them to chew large lumps of Gum; so large as to cause them inconvenience in hot dry weather and water scarce</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I also send you a sprig in flower of that acacia we call Yarron.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>APNI lists a number of species to which 'Yarron' has been applied, including<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">A.</seg>
                        <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">homalophylla</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">, as does Morris (1898), p. 523.</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>The<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Australian national dictionary</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>restricts its use (as 'yarran' or 'yarren') to<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">A. homalophylla</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>It is often gregarious and forms Yarron scrubs for 7 feet high. I have known detached trees 30 or more feet high with a Trunk of 5 or 6 feet &amp; about a foot through The wood is fragrant. It does not grow so big as the Boree nor is it like it a good fodder plant. There is another acacia like this nearer the Murrumbidgie the flower of which is much the size and shape of the European Rib-grass – a Plantain – but of a Yellow Colour of course</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">In Haste</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Baron</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have the honor to be</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your very obedient Servt</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>A. N. Grant</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">P.S. I omitted to mention that I think the decurrens would not grow in such dry country as this one frequents; it also seems very rich in Tannin. Pray excuse this scrawl. I will endeavour to procure seeds for you</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">A. N. G.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">The Baron von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plantnames"
               style="font-style: italic; font-size: 10pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Acacia decurrens</p>
         </div>
      </body>
